WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.900
Good day , I'm Norman Wildberger, and today&nbsp;
we're going to introduce the rational numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:12.900 --> 00:00:17.850
the first and most important example of&nbsp;
what in mathematics is called a field,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:17.850 --> 00:00:21.960
which is roughly a domain in which&nbsp;
we can do addition, multiplication,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:21.960 --> 00:00:26.040
subtraction, and division in&nbsp;
a complete and consistent way.

00:00:26.040 --> 00:00:31.800
So the story up till now is that we've&nbsp;
started with the natural numbers and then&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:31.800 --> 00:00:40.890
we introduced the fractions by dividing, and we&nbsp;
introduced the integers by subtracting. We want&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:40.890 --> 00:00:45.600
to now go from the integers to the rational&nbsp;
numbers in just the same way as we went from&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:45.600 --> 00:00:52.320
the natural numbers to the fractions. That is, we&nbsp;
want to augment the integers by allowing division.

00:00:52.320 --> 00:00:59.940
So let's just make sure we understand what these&nbsp;
various terms mean. By "number," I mean natural&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:59.940 --> 00:01:07.560
numbers in Hindu-Arabic notation, things like&nbsp;
1, 2, 3, and so on. By "fraction," I mean an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:07.560 --> 00:01:14.310
expression of the form 2 over 3 or 3 over 1,&nbsp;
where the constituents are natural numbers. By&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:14.310 --> 00:01:21.720
"integer," I mean an expression of the form&nbsp;
1 less 2 or 3 less 1, where again, 1 and 2,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:21.720 --> 00:01:29.190
3 and 1 are natural numbers. What we're going to&nbsp;
do is use these integers to form rational numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:29.190 --> 00:01:35.760
and a rational number is going to be just&nbsp;
like this: an integer over another integer.

00:01:35.760 --> 00:01:41.700
Here's the official definition: A&nbsp;
rational number is an ordered pair (a,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:41.700 --> 00:01:51.390
b), where a and b are integers and b is not equal&nbsp;
to zero. And I'll explain that in a second. We&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:51.390 --> 00:01:59.580
write this ordered pair (a, b) as a/b, just the&nbsp;
same way as we write a fraction. What is zero?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:59.580 --> 00:02:07.920
Zero is a special integer; it's the integer&nbsp;
1 less 1, which is also equal to 2 less 2 or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:07.920 --> 00:02:16.790
3 less 3. So we require that the second integer&nbsp;
is not equal to zero when we form this quotient.

00:02:18.620 --> 00:02:24.860
There's an important notion of equality that&nbsp;
you'll not be surprised by now: that a/b is equal&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:24.860 --> 00:02:35.330
to c/d precisely when ad equals bc, when this&nbsp;
times this equals this times this. So that's what&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:35.330 --> 00:02:44.540
a rational number is, and we denote that type by&nbsp;
the symbol ℚ, which stands for a rational number.

00:02:44.540 --> 00:02:52.520
Now let's introduce some notation that makes&nbsp;
rational numbers look more familiar. Let's start&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:52.520 --> 00:03:01.250
with the integer 1 less 2. We will write that in&nbsp;
the more familiar way as -1, and we'll agree that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:01.250 --> 00:03:07.430
3 less 1 is written in the more familiar way&nbsp;
as 2, even though there remains a possibility&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:07.430 --> 00:03:12.380
of confusing integers with natural numbers.&nbsp;
Officially, we want to keep them straight.

00:03:12.380 --> 00:03:21.380
More generally, if we have m less n, then there&nbsp;
are three possibilities: if m is bigger than n,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:21.380 --> 00:03:27.980
then this is equal to m minus n, and we will&nbsp;
write it as m minus n. If n is bigger than m,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:27.980 --> 00:03:31.220
then we'll get what we usually call a&nbsp;
negative number, and we will write it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:31.220 --> 00:03:38.630
as minus (n minus m). That's if n is&nbsp;
bigger than m. If m and n are equal,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:38.630 --> 00:03:42.020
then we'll just use the symbol&nbsp;
zero, as we've already introduced.

00:03:42.020 --> 00:03:46.100
Now a little bit of notation for rational numbers:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:46.100 --> 00:03:55.010
1 less 2 over 3 less 1. Now that we've&nbsp;
got a name for 1 less 2, we call it -1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:55.010 --> 00:04:03.890
and 3 less 1, we call that 2. So this rational&nbsp;
number can be expressed as -1/2. We will also&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:03.890 --> 00:04:11.240
introduce the other standard notation that when&nbsp;
we have 1 in the denominator, such as 3/1, then&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:11.240 --> 00:04:20.510
we'll abbreviate that to be 3. We'll abbreviate&nbsp;
0/1 to be 0, 1/1 to be 1, and so on. That way,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:20.510 --> 00:04:26.400
the natural numbers fit inside the rational&nbsp;
numbers, but it's a little bit of a deception&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:26.400 --> 00:04:32.400
because officially rational numbers, natural&nbsp;
numbers, and integers are all separate types.

00:04:32.400 --> 00:04:41.520
Now we can define the main operations for&nbsp;
rational numbers. First of all, addition:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:41.520 --> 00:04:49.530
if we have a/b + c/d, then we use exactly&nbsp;
the familiar form for fractions. The sum&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:49.530 --> 00:04:57.120
is defined to be (ad + bc) / bd. Here, a,&nbsp;
b, c, and d are integers. The product a/b&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:57.690 --> 00:05:06.210
times c/d is by definition (a * c) /&nbsp;
(b * d). Then the inverse operations,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:06.210 --> 00:05:14.280
subtraction and division, are easily&nbsp;
obtained: a/b minus c/d is (ad - bc) / bd,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:14.280 --> 00:05:27.930
and a/b divided by c/d, which we also write&nbsp;
a/b ÷ c/d, is equal to (a * d) / (b * c).

00:05:27.930 --> 00:05:31.560
So those are the four main operations,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:31.560 --> 00:05:37.020
and there's just a bit of qualification in&nbsp;
all of these. The denominators cannot be 0,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:37.020 --> 00:05:42.720
and when we divide, we have to make sure&nbsp;
that c is not equal to 0, because otherwise&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:42.720 --> 00:05:47.910
we would be dividing by 0. So division by&nbsp;
0 is not allowed; otherwise, we're fine.

00:05:49.680 --> 00:05:55.650
The rational numbers are now what is&nbsp;
called a field. This is a technical term in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:55.650 --> 00:06:00.930
mathematics, and we want to be precise about what&nbsp;
it means. So we'll say that the rational numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:00.930 --> 00:06:05.550
which is a type of object together with the&nbsp;
operations of addition and multiplication,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:05.550 --> 00:06:11.640
form a field. What does that mean? Well,&nbsp;
it means that various laws are satisfied:

00:06:12.870 --> 00:06:22.620
The associative laws: P + (Q + R) = (P&nbsp;
+ Q) + R and P * (Q * R) = (P * Q) * R.&nbsp;

00:06:22.620 --> 00:06:30.000
The commutative laws: P + Q&nbsp;
= Q + P and P * Q = Q * P.&nbsp;

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:38.160
Then we have some special elements, three special&nbsp;
elements in fact: ones that we call zero, one, and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:38.160 --> 00:06:45.480
minus one, and they have the following properties:
0 + P = P (so we say that zero is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:45.480 --> 00:06:51.780
an additive identity),
1 * P = P (that means for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:51.780 --> 00:07:00.960
any P, one is a multiplicative identity),
and that 1 + (-1) together add up to zero.&nbsp;

00:07:03.480 --> 00:07:07.740
There's another property called the&nbsp;
inverse property: if you have any&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:07.740 --> 00:07:14.850
element P which is not zero, then there should&nbsp;
be another element Q, sometimes denoted P⁻¹,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:15.930 --> 00:07:23.880
which has the property that P * Q = 1. So&nbsp;
every element P has an inverse one so that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:23.880 --> 00:07:29.010
when you multiply the two of them, you get one.
Finally, the distributive law that connects&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:29.010 --> 00:07:36.120
multiplication and addition: P&nbsp;
* (Q + R) = (P * Q) + (P * R).&nbsp;

00:07:38.100 --> 00:07:45.810
Now it's an important exercise to verify that the&nbsp;
rational numbers, together with the operations&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:45.810 --> 00:07:54.540
that we've defined, satisfy all of these laws.&nbsp;
There's nothing really new in doing this, and I'm&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:54.540 --> 00:07:58.950
not going to do it because it would take me a few&nbsp;
videos to do, but it's an excellent exercise for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:58.950 --> 00:08:03.870
a graduate student or an undergraduate who's&nbsp;
interested in understanding how mathematics&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:03.870 --> 00:08:10.500
really works. It's something that's often not&nbsp;
done properly, but it's an important exercise.

00:08:10.500 --> 00:08:16.110
The rational numbers are the first&nbsp;
example of a field, and later on,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:16.110 --> 00:08:21.360
we'll introduce other examples of fields.&nbsp;
It's very important to recognize, though,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:21.360 --> 00:08:26.070
that the rational numbers are the most&nbsp;
important field. They always work;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:26.070 --> 00:08:32.520
they always will be. People might try to convince&nbsp;
you that the real numbers or the complex numbers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:32.520 --> 00:08:36.540
or something else are more important. It's&nbsp;
not the case. The rational numbers, which&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:36.540 --> 00:08:43.020
we've spent a fair amount of time developing, are&nbsp;
always the most important field in mathematics.

00:08:43.020 --> 00:08:49.360
Next time, we're going to have a look&nbsp;
at how to visualize rational numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:49.870 --> 00:08:54.190
and we're going to connect rational numbers&nbsp;
to a remarkable set of objects called Ford&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:54.190 --> 00:09:00.460
circles. It's going to give us some really&nbsp;
beautiful geometrical insight into the nature&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:00.460 --> 00:09:05.920
of rational numbers. I hope you're going&nbsp;
to join me for that. I'm Norman Wildberger.

